    "title": "Vacuous Truth: “Nothing is an absolute reality; all is permitted.” ",
    "description": "Once, during a field trip to the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, I passed by a riverside village where people were holding a funeral for a deceased villager. At the funeral, a middle-aged man wearing a wooden mask that features Sun Wukong, also known as the Monkey King, a legendary figure in ancient Chinese mythology, climbed onto the head of the coffin and performed somersaults, handstands and other difficult movements in the accompaniment of gongs and drums. Hundreds of villagers attending the funeral stood around, watching in silence.<br/>This strange funeral ceremony is astonishing. Perhaps people devised such a way of burial to vent their grief. <br/>One of myriad funeral rites, this ceremony is closely associated with local customs, environment and culture, among other factors. <br/>Through these works, I want to express the independence or isolation of humanity, how this isolation is associated with landscapes and how I have discovered myself in these scenes. ",
